12.55pm: Five mins or so until the start - here's Saurabh to talk you through the opening stages.

Ramesh: "Who is the 6th bowler for England? Top 6 is full of wicket Keepers." -- Root might get a few overs, I'd suggest. Though they only used five on Friday.

My colleague Saurabh Somani points out that this is the first time the Currans will be part of the same England XI in a home international.

Here's CA's statement on Smith's absence: "Steve passed both assessments, but we have decided to rest him as an extra precaution in line with our high level of focus on duty of care to all players"

Bill Lee: "Moeen's stats does indeed look awful, but is there anyone knocking on the door to replace him?" -- That's the big question, I guess. Livingstone does a different job, and I'm not sure they'd want to pick two specialist leggies with Parkinson (and Crane) next in the pecking order. So... Dawson?

Wonder if this is the beginning of the end for Moeen in ODIs for England? He was a key cog between his debut and 2017, but his record in the last two years is pretty ugly and he'll be 37 come the next WC. That said, England don't have many like-for-like replacements: Liam Dawson is the closest, but is currently injured, has a lower ceiling, and spins the ball the same direction as Rashid.

Otto: "Bizarre that Finch wasn't questioned about Smith absence" -- Agreed! CA told us he had passed his second concussion test yesterday and would be good to go. Let's hope he's OK.

England: 1 Jason Roy, 2 Jonny Bairstow, 3 Joe Root, 4 Eoin Morgan (captain), 5 Jos Buttler (wk), 6 Sam Billings, 7 Sam Curran, 8 Chris Woakes, 9 Tom Curran, 10 Adil Rashid, 11 Jofra Archer

Australia: 1 David Warner, 2 Aaron Finch (captain), 3 Marcus Stoinis, 4 Marnus Labuschagne, 5 Mitchell Marsh, 6 Alex Carey (wk), 7 Glenn Maxwell, 8 Pat Cummins, 9 Mitchell Starc, 10 Adam Zampa, 11 Josh Hazlewood

Morgan and Finch are in the middle. The coin goes up, and England will bat first after winning the toss. "It's the same wicket as the other day," Morgan says. "It might potentially get a little bit worse this afternoon. It probably didn't spin as much as we thought it was going to [on Friday] but if you hit the right area, there's a bit on offer." The Currans are in for Wood [rested, ankle niggle] and Moeen [tactical decision].

"We'd have batted first on this wicket, it being a used wicket," says Finch. "We've gone with the same team. Starc is fine, he's ready to go. The way we fought back against the spin was really impressive and in the first ten overs we bowled nicely." No Smith after all - no mention of his absence at the toss. We'll bring you any news on that as we get it.

12.25pm: They're using the same pitch today, by the way, so expect this to follow a similar pattern to the first game - it could be hard work for batsmen against the new ball, and 250 or so could be a handy first-innings total. Five minutes until the toss.

12.10pm: Mitchell Marsh may be the butt of the joke more often than not, but he has quietly put together a decent run over the last 12 months or so in one-day cricket. Andrew McGlashan wrote about his role in the side ahead of this one. Meanwhile, Billings knows that despite his innings on Friday, he remains an understudy for the time being.

"Beautiful day in Manchester," reports our man in the bubble, George Dobell. Makes a nice change!

12.00pm: Hello and welcome to ESPNcricinfo's live ball-by-ball coverage of the 2nd ODI between England and Australia in Manchester. Australia got across the line despite stumbling to 123 for 5 on Friday, with Glenn Maxwell's pyrotechnics complementing Mitchell Marsh's grit to propel them up towards 300. England's chase never got started, and despite a superb maiden international hundred from Sam Billings, they never really looked like getting over the line. They need a win today to avoid a first ODI series defeat at home since 2015. I'm Matt Roller and will be joined by Saurabh Somani to talk you through this one.
